From b122e280cb050f0229dce193e7107cd2766799b5 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: UX Redesign <design@medpath.local>
Date: Tue, 30 Jun 2026 04:22:38 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 4/4] Fix Reports page: dark mode contrast, padding, grid
 layout
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The report sheet (patient band, footer, group titles, table headers)
hardcoded light-mode hex colors with no dark variant, so in dark
mode all labels (PATIENT NAME, AGE/SEX, REFERRED BY, etc.), the
section title, table headers, and footer sign-off text were nearly
invisible — pale teal text on a pale teal-tinted-white fallback
background that never adapted to the dark surface.

- Add report-sheet-specific design tokens (--rpt-band-bg,
  --rpt-tint-bg, --rpt-note-bg, --rpt-crit-bg, etc.) to both the
  light and dark LIS token blocks in styles.css, so the document
  has its own theme-aware palette instead of scattered hardcoded
  hex fallbacks
- Rewrite reports.component.css to consume these tokens throughout
  (patient band, title band, note banner, critical-row highlight,
  table headers/ref column, footer) — verified legible in both
  themes via rendered screenshot comparison
- Widen the report-list grid column (288px -> 320px, with a
  responsive step at 1100px) so patient name + meta + status pill
  no longer risk crowding/wrapping
- Add minmax(0, 1fr) to the preview column so the report sheet's
  table content can't push the grid wider than the page
- Add proper vertical inset to the report-list row container so
  rows aren't flush against the card's rounded corners
- Add box-shadow elevation to the report-sheet so it reads as a
  distinct document instead of blending into the page background
  (most noticeable in dark mode, where it had zero separation)
- Add a left accent bar to the selected list row for a clearer
  'currently viewing' indicator
- Add the missing @else empty state ('Select a report...') for
  when selected() is null — previously nothing rendered at all
- Wrap the results table in a scroll container with a sane
  min-width so columns don't get crushed/clipped on narrow
  viewports instead of just shrinking illegibly
- Make the patient info band responsive (3 -> 2 -> 1 columns)
  instead of a fixed 3-column grid that crowded on mobile
